post_text:
Friday is PATRIOT DAY!!! We will be recognizing this throughout our school district. Patriot Day on September 11th honors the memory of the nearly 3,000 innocent victims who died in the September 11, 2001, terrorist attacks. Each year Americans dedicate this day to remembering those who died and to the first responders who risked their own lives to save others. Here are a few ideas for that day!!
1. Wear red, white, and blue.
2. Discuss the events as appropriate in our classrooms.
3. Moment of silence (first plane hit 8:46am EST, then 9:03am EST, 9:37am EST, and 10:03am EST)
4. Use #PatriotDay or #NeverForget on your social media to show your support.

post_text: Good Morning! This morning (Tuesday) we have some flurries but the brunt should hit later today. I am thankful for warm pavement!! Parents...please know that we know many of you live in locations that are more difficult to get in and out of. Today is our first day of all kids coming back for Phase 3. Both of those things being said, you may feel the need to have your child out early from school (it is all supposed to start hitting around 3:00) or it isn't safe to travel from where you live. That is OK and we completely support you. Once we get kids to school we try to not excuse early because we don't want to send kids home to empty homes - especially our elementary kids. If you choose to take them home early - no problem. Stay safe and warm!!!! - Steve

post_text: SNOWDAY/VIRTUAL DAY???? Fitting with the 2020 theme, we have a winter storm watch in our school district during the summer. post_text: It is with great sadness that we let you know that our beloved former mayor, high school baseball coach, and friend to all, Neil Levy, has passed away this morning. Neil leaves an amazing legacy in our schools, community, and in the lives of all who had the pleasure of knowing him. Services will be live streamed and announced later with just the family in physical attendance. Our thoughts and prayers go out to his wife, Paula, his sons and family, and all of the people who have had the pleasure of loving and being loved by Neil. Well done, Neil… well done.
text: It is with great sadness that we let you know that our beloved former mayor, high school baseball coach, and friend to all, Neil Levy, has passed away this morning. Neil leaves an amazing legacy in our schools, community, and in the lives of all who had the pleasure of knowing him. Services will be live streamed and announced later with just the family in physical attendance. Our thoughts and prayers go out to his wife, Paula, his sons and family, and all of the people who have had the pleasure of loving and being loved by Neil. Well done, Neil… well done.

SENIORS!!! PARENTS OF SENIORS!!!! $1,000 Could you use an extra $1,000 of scholarship money for college? KIWANIS just gave away three $1,000 scholarships to the three seniors who already applied. They decided to do two more!! Here is what you need to do by May 15...
Of course, it will have to be all on-line. Submit the following to us,(loydandcandy@gmail.com)
1. Full Name, parent contact phone numbers and addresses
2. Current Transcript
3. 2 letters of recommendation
4. A cover letter of introduction, including community service, school activities, work experience, why you need or deserve the scholarship, and what you do in your spare time.

post_text:
During a press conference this afternoon, Colorado Governor Jared Polis announced the suspension of in-person learning across our state through April 30, 2020. This order aligns with the President’s guidelines announced earlier this week.

Woodland Park School District will therefore remain on our current path of Remote Learning through April 30. The District will send more details around the April break in the coming weeks.

Please know, we continue to work closely with the Governor and are following the recommendations of state and regional health professionals. The health and safety of our students and staff remains our top priority.
text:
During a press conference this afternoon, Colorado Governor Jared Polis announced the suspension of in-person learning across our state through April 30, 2020. This order aligns with the President’s guidelines announced earlier this week.

Woodland Park School District will therefore remain on our current path of Remote Learning through April 30. The District will send more details around the April break in the coming weeks.

Next week (March 23-27) is officially Spring Break. Remote Learning will begin on Tuesday, March 31. Administration and teachers are currently preparing what that will look like for each grade level and will be communicating that information to you soon.

A survey was sent to all families regarding your individual needs. If you do not receive this, please go to our website (wpsdk12.org) to access the survey link.

WPSD will provide sack meals at no cost beginning on Monday, March 30 between 11 a.m. to 2 p.m. for students. This “Grab and Go” service will be provided Monday-Friday, including weekend food on Fridays. There will be three pick-up locations:
*Woodland Park: Gateway Elementary School
*Divide: Summit Elementary School
*Florissant: Site TBD

At this time, we are planning for everyone to return to school on Tuesday, April 21 (with Monday, April 20 a staff work day). If that date changes, we will notify parents as soon as possible.

Stay healthy and safe!

post_text: As we come to the close to National Public School week, I wanted to take a moment to thank our community for the support of our staffulty in our schools! Our folks would literally lay down their lives for our kids and are not getting rich doing it. We do what we do out of love. We live in a society where many do not get that it is easy to judge one's character by their ability to "praise in public and correct in private." If you get a chance, please lift up our amazing staffulty for what they do to make a life long difference in the lives of our kids! Thank you!!!!

post_text:
New school hours starting on Feb. 24 will be as follows:

Columbine: Start time: 7:35 a.m. – Release time: 2:50 p.m.
Gateway: Start time: 7:45 a.m. – Release time: 3 p.m.
Summit: Start time: 8:50 a.m. – Release time: 4:05 p.m.
WPMS: Start time: 7:38 a.m. – Release time: 3 p.m.
WPHS: Start time: 7:43 a.m. – Release time: 3:10 p.m.

As with other districts around the region, WPSD needs to add time to our school day to ensure that we meet the state required hours for the school year. Minimal time requirements vary per level with more time required for secondary students. While we hoped to balance the demand across the District with our secondary virtual days, we now find the need for additional time in other areas. Given the fact that our bus routes run in coordination across the District, we worked with Durham to arrive at new school hours that will take effect starting Monday, Feb. 24th and run through the end of the school year. We appreciate your patience and flexibility as we strive to adjust to unpredictable Colorado weather and keep our students safe.

post_text: Remember the annual WPHS Madrigals Dinner is this Friday, Dec. 6 and again on Saturday, Dec. 7 at 7 p.m. in the high school commons. The evening includes a delicious 3-course meal and a Renaissance-themed performance including kings, queens, knights, a castle and, of course, a joker! There will be plenty of laughter and good tidings to kick off the holiday season! Buy tickets at: https://wphsmadrigals.seatyourself.biz

The Panthers finished the regular season with a standout 21-2 record, going undefeated in the Colorado Springs Metro League.

This Saturday the Panthers will host Colorado High School Activities Association 4A Regionals at home! #gopanthers

post_text: Super Volunteer, Rose Banzhaf, has been awarded the 2019 AVS Teaching Award for Excellence in Teaching Informal Education Science for Colorado!!!! We are so proud of the work Rose does in our schools and community!! WPSD is the top Environment and Conservation district in Colorado and much of this is attributed to Rose's great work as a super volunteer in our district!! THANK YOU ROSE!!!!

shared_text:
Woodland Park Football
November 3, 2019 at 6:05 AM ·

What a crazy weekend for Panther Football! JV lost their match up, finishing with a 6-3 season. As for the varsity, well they defended home field against the 4th ranked team in the state!! They won their final game of the regular season 28-20 and finish the season 5-4. Go Panthers!

#WoodlandParkPanthers #WpFootball🏈 #PantherPride🐾 #BrotherHood #GreenAndWhite #Relentless #ColoradoHighSchoolFootball #chsaa #EDGE
